Other than that, it was a good, fun film.

One thing I like is the film is that it respects the audience intelligence. It gives us The Red Herrings in the form of subversions, so that the viewer will take it for granted. For example It seems like Ransom is set up as the JerkAss of the mostly nice family, so it seems the subversion is that Ransom is actually a nice guy after the rest of the families true nature is revealed. And of course there's the plot itself. It seems like the Subversion comes when were told what the answer to the Mystery is in the first act.
And then the 3rd act comes around and Subverts the Subversions

snippet.textDisplay:
How is it even POSSIBLE on this EARTH that you have never done a "wins" video for GATTACA? Remember the original idea for the channel? Movies which were underrated or underperformed, but had much more to them than they were given credit for? Well, THERE IT SITS, the prototypical movie for this channel, unwinned! I mean, whether it's Michael Nyman's score or the thematic parallels between this story and writer/director Andrew Niccol's sophomore effort, the lauded Truman Show (hint: Truman and Vincent are the same character, with the difference being that Vincent knows that he's in a cage not of his own making, and Truman does not. They even have their climactic moment in the waters!) or the fact that the movie has more always-a-win actors than you can shake a stick at (including, but not limited to Tony Shaloub, Blair Underwood, Xander Berkeley, the living treasure which is Una Damon, Maya Rudolph, Alan Arkin, and Ernest-frakkin'-Borgnine), or whether it's the use of color or symbolism - did I mention Michael Nyman's score-? or parallelism, or the fact that this movie called it on select-a-trait babies before it was a thing in the real world . . . Gattaca has all that you could want in a win video, and the ONLY reason everybody doesn't know about it is that it was completely mismarketed as an action thriller.

Seriously. You really need to consider doing this movie. It's a . . . well, it's a shame, at least, that you haven't done it long before now.

snippet.textDisplay: I gotta say, I think one of my favourite things among a plethora of favourite things about this movie is how Ransom is kind of introduced. snippet.textDisplay:
I wasn't a huge fan of this film. I don't know whether or not I'm just too naive (or something) but I never believed Marta to have accidentally gave him the wrong dosage. It didn't ruin it for me, but I knew that would be one way Rian "fooled" the audience and "subverted" expectations in a way that he does that doesn't work for me. I think it was a well made film for the most part and I completely understand why people love it. I'm thrilled to see a film in this genre get the attention it received, and by all means deserved.


The only part that I think was executed poorly was the political side, seeming very shallow, undeveloped, poor representations of both sides of the argument and is more of a parody of how little Hollywood actually understands politics. I don't understand how someone stating someone is a SJW or Alt-right Nazi makes them such. It's even mentioned that the family is all a bunch of unreliable narrators, why are we supposed to care about their politics, when it doesn't matter to the plot and we're given no reason to believe them anyways? The whole family dynamic for me ruined the film beyond redemption, convinced my why films that have zero to do w/ politics should stay the hell away from them.


I love Ana de Armas and Daniel Craig's performances and can't wait to see them in the upcoming bond film. I'm sure I'll see the sequel to knives out, but I unfortunately don't love this film as much as I was hoping for. By all means, I hope that anyone that enjoys this film continues to enjoy it, I was hoping these videos would've helped me change my view on it but they just cemented them more.


Video was great content as always.

snippet.textDisplay: I love this movie and I loved hearing your thoughts on it! Buuuuuut... saying the movie didn't come down too hard on one side or the other in the "immigration subplot" is disingenuous: Marta is good in many ways because she is an immigrant, because she's lived through hardships with her mother and sister and because she's worked hard to get where she is! The Thrombeys are almost all asshats because they are rich, which is Harlan's whole point: he handed them everything they could ever want in life on a silver platter and that made them self-absorbed, bigoted, lazy and greedy. You have a tendency of trying to come across as centrist in a lot of these videos, and on this platform of all platforms I get it, but it's okay to acknowledge the themes and messages of a story in more detail, especially when they're all but spelled out for you lmao. Keep up the good work, I'm definitely gonna keep on watching <3

snippet.textDisplay: A lot of people write off the immigration subplot as "just another way RUIN Johnson is pandering to liberal Hollywood" but if you're paying attention it's way deeper and smarter than that. Like you pointed out, what sets Marta apart from the Thrombeys is that she's a genuinely good person, completely divorced from any political ideology, whereas every member of the family clearly feels superior, and uses their political beliefs to justify it. But when push comes to shove, and the Thrombeys feel threatened they all backslide into taking a decidedly anti-immigration stance to get their money back, revealing that they're not good people, regardless of how they think their politics defines them. Of course this is also layered in with moments like none of the Thrombeys knowing where Marta is from, or by treating her like the maid, but I think it was smart to have it laid out plainly, and let members of the audience sympathize with various members of the family depending on their personal beliefs, and have the rug ripped out from under them when the whole family turns on Marta. Anyways, this script is brilliant, and I hope people were able to set aside their personal biases towards Rian Johnson and just enjoy the movie on its own terms.
